(154, 173, 'Publication', NULL, '0', '1', 'https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S002216940000278X', 'RO4T7pcAAAAJ;Yvg9IkIAAAAJ', 1474, '/scholar?q=info:zlPNI7QgM90J:scholar.google.com/&output=cite&scirp=0&hl=en', '/citations?hl=en&xsrf=&continue=/scholar%3Fq%3D%2BBates,%2BP.D.,%2BRoo,%2BA.P.J.D.,%2BA%2Bsimple%2Braster-based%2Bmodel%2Bfor%2Bflood%2Binundation%2Bsimulation%2B(2000)%2BJ.%2BHydrol.,%2B236,%2Bpp.%2B54-77%26hl%3Den%26as_sdt%3D0,33&citilm=1&json=&update_op=library_add&info=zlPNI7QgM90J&ei=m3WTYKzFBrCBy9YPrM-NiAY', '/scholar?cites=15939119464261178318&as_sdt=5,33&sciodt=0,33&hl=en', '/scholar?q=related:zlPNI7QgM90J:scholar.google.com/&scioq=+Bates,+P.D.,+Roo,+A.P.J.D.,+A+simple+raster-based+model+for+flood+inundation+simulation+(2000)+J.+Hydrol.,+236,+pp.+54-77&hl=en&as_sdt=0,33', 'A simple raster-based model for flood inundation simulation', 'PD Bates;APJ De Roo', 2000, 'Journal of hydrology', 'In this paper the development of a new model for simulating flood inundation is outlined. The model is designed to operate with high-resolution raster Digital Elevation Models, which are becoming increasingly available for many lowland floodplain rivers and is based on what we hypothesise to be the simplest possible process representation capable of simulating dynamic flood inundation. This consists of a one-dimensional kinematic wave approximation for channel flow solved using an explicit finite difference scheme and a two-dimensional'),
(155, 174, 'Publication', NULL, '0', '1', 'https://advances.sciencemag.org/content/5/9/eaaw5531.abstract', 'YXvyyQEAAAAJ;XfJ7CC0AAAAJ;OiUePPcAAAAJ', 71, '/scholar?q=info:-6XeyVYYDYkJ:scholar.google.com/&output=cite&scirp=0&hl=en', '/citations?hl=en&xsrf=&continue=/scholar%3Fq%3D%2B(2019),%2BBevacqua,%2BMaraun,%2BD.,%2BVousdoukas,%2BM.I.,%2BVoukouvalas,%2BE.,%2BVrac,%2BM.,%2BMentaschi,%2BL.,%2BWidmann,%2BM.%2BHigher%2Bprobability%2Bof%2Bcompound%2Bflooding%2Bfrom%2Bprecipitation%2Band%2Bstorm%2Bsurge%2Bin%2BEurope%2Bunder%2Banthropogenic%2Bclimate%2Bchange.%2BSci.%2BAdv.%2B5,%2Beaaw5531.%2Bdoi:%26hl%3Den%26as_sdt%3D0,33&citilm=1&json=&update_op=library_add&info=-6XeyVYYDYkJ&ei=nXWTYNKhK-TTsQLdgI_YAw', '/scholar?cites=9875576318926431739&as_sdt=5,33&sciodt=0,33&hl=en', '/scholar?q=related:-6XeyVYYDYkJ:scholar.google.com/&scioq=+(2019),+Bevacqua,+Maraun,+D.,+Vousdoukas,+M.I.,+Voukouvalas,+E.,+Vrac,+M.,+Mentaschi,+L.,+Widmann,+M.+Higher+probability+of+compound+flooding+from+precipitation+and+storm+surge+in+Europe+under+anthropogenic+climate+change.+Sci.+Adv.+5,+eaaw5531.+doi:&hl=en&as_sdt=0,33', 'Higher probability of compound flooding from precipitation and storm surge in Europe under anthropogenic climate change', 'E Bevacqua;D Maraun;MI Vousdoukas', 2019, 'Science …', 'In low-lying coastal areas, the co-occurrence of high sea level and precipitation resulting in large runoff may cause compound flooding (CF). When the two hazards interact, the resulting impact can be worse than when they occur individually. Both storm surges and heavy precipitation, as well as their interplay, are likely to change in response to global warming. Despite the CF relevance, a comprehensive hazard assessment beyond individual locations is missing, and no studies have examined CF in the future. Analyzing co-occurring'),
(156, 175, 'Publication', NULL, '0', '1', 'https://nhess.copernicus.org/articles/20/1765/2020/', 'YXvyyQEAAAAJ;OiUePPcAAAAJ', 7, '/scholar?q=info:nUZAJ22M2g0J:scholar.google.com/&output=cite&scirp=0&hl=en', '/citations?hl=en&xsrf=&continue=/scholar%3Fq%3D%2BBevacqua,%2BE.,%2BVousdoukas,%2BM.I.,%2BShepherd,%2BT.G.,%2BVrac,%2BM.,%2BBrief%2Bcommunication:%2Bthe%2Brole%2Bof%2Busing%2Bprecipitation%2Bor%2Briver%2Bdischarge%2Bdata%2Bwhen%2Bassessing%2Bglobal%2Bcoastal%2Bcompound%2Bflooding%2B(2020)%2BNat.%2BHazards%2BEarth%2BSyst.%2BSci.,%2B20,%2Bpp.%2B1765-1782%26hl%3Den%26as_sdt%3D0,33&citilm=1&json=&update_op=library_add&info=nUZAJ22M2g0J&ei=n3WTYOW8MILCsQKw15L4DA', '/scholar?cites=998264667853833885&as_sdt=5,33&sciodt=0,33&hl=en', '/scholar?q=related:nUZAJ22M2g0J:scholar.google.com/&scioq=+Bevacqua,+E.,+Vousdoukas,+M.I.,+Shepherd,+T.G.,+Vrac,+M.,+Brief+communication:+the+role+of+using+precipitation+or+river+discharge+data+when+assessing+global+coastal+compound+flooding+(2020)+Nat.+Hazards+Earth+Syst.+Sci.,+20,+pp.+1765-1782&hl=en&as_sdt=0,33', 'Brief communication: The role of using precipitation or river discharge data when assessing global coastal compound flooding', 'E Bevacqua;MI Vousdoukas', 2020, 'Natural Hazards and …', 'Interacting storm surges and high water runoff can cause compound flooding (CF) in low-lying coasts and river estuaries. The large-scale CF hazard has been typically studied using proxies such as the concurrence of storm surge extremes either with precipitation or with river discharge extremes. Here the impact of the choice of such proxies is addressed employing state-of-the-art global datasets. Although they are proxies of diverse physical mechanisms, we find that the two approaches show similar CF spatial patterns. On average'),
(157, 176, 'Publication', NULL, '0', '1', 'https://agupubs.onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/abs/10.1002/2018GL077524', 'hdjJzY0AAAAJ;3EWqjHoAAAAJ', 34, '/scholar?q=info:fP9gbZ5pSewJ:scholar.google.com/&output=cite&scirp=0&hl=en', '/citations?hl=en&xsrf=&continue=/scholar%3Fq%3D%2BBilskie,%2BM.V.,%2BHagen,%2BS.C.,%2BDefining%2Bflood%2Bzone%2Btransitions%2Bin%2Blow-gradient%2Bcoastal%2Bregions%2B(2018)%2BGeophys.%2BRes.%2BLett.,%2B45,%2Bpp.%2B2761-2770%26hl%3Den%26as_sdt%3D0,33&citilm=1&json=&update_op=library_add&info=fP9gbZ5pSewJ&ei=oXWTYKqdL8KLy9YPvcOdyAo', '/scholar?cites=17026255995411693436&as_sdt=5,33&sciodt=0,33&hl=en', '/scholar?q=related:fP9gbZ5pSewJ:scholar.google.com/&scioq=+Bilskie,+M.V.,+Hagen,+S.C.,+Defining+flood+zone+transitions+in+low-gradient+coastal+regions+(2018)+Geophys.+Res.+Lett.,+45,+pp.+2761-2770&hl=en&as_sdt=0,33', 'Defining flood zone transitions in low‐gradient coastal regions', 'MV Bilskie;SC Hagen', 2018, 'Geophysical Research Letters', 'Worldwide, coastal, and deltaic communities are susceptible to flooding from the individual and combined effects of rainfall excess and astronomic tide and storm surge inundation. Such flood events are a present (and future) cause of concern as observed from recent storms such as the 2016 Louisiana flood and Hurricanes Harvey, Irma, and Maria. To assess flood risk across coastal landscapes, it is advantageous to first delineate flood transition zones, which we define as areas susceptible to hydrologic and coastal flooding and their'),
